issue.title: getMailMIME and Custom Headers
issue.body:
In this section, https://github.com/PHPMailer/PHPMailer/blob/0ff2d3c8ead628df2493537d9f91db962aa47718/src/PHPMailer.php#L2838-L2860

Message types are selected based on certain other attributes. 
For example. An alt message type, is based on the fact that the message already has a "AltBody" 

If we set a Custom Header, with whatever ContentType and/or boundary, if such attributes are not set, it will go to default, and break despite both the headers and the body could be correctly formed. 

# Problem description
The problem here is that this default option doesn't leave margin for potential customizations. Current implementation forces strict elements (like AltBody), that could not necessarily align with a correctly formatted email.

# Code to reproduce
I'm coming from here on WordPress:
https://github.com/WordPress/wordpress-develop/blob/6ea383f14783604934af91c60fee9471a40974df/src/wp-includes/pluggable.php#L517-L519

As we can see in this line, what it does is the following:
- First check if it contains the multipart text in the header, and if the boundary is not empty. In this case, we have stated that this is Multipart Content Type
- Then it adds the custom header, which is the Content-Type and the boundary.  

This is sent like this to PHPMailer. PHPMailer receives this, goes to default because AltBody is probably missing, and wipes the boundary because the default condition doesn't require a boundary. 

The result: 2 `Content-Type: multipart` Headers, and the email broken.

The solution: Maybe the default condition should be a little more flexible. Currently, we are working on a patch for WordPress, to allow creating Multipart content, based on a specific body message, which has to be specifically made as an array. But for a message that is simply a string, this will always fail, regardless if the email is perfectly formatted.

Check this example: 
https://core.trac.wordpress.org/ticket/15448?replyto=70#comment:70

```
$body = '--TestBoundary
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8

This is a test email body.
--TestBoundary
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8
<html><body>This is a test email body.</body></html>
--TestBoundary--
';
$headers = [
	'Example-Custom: value',
	'Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="TestBoundary"',
];

wp_mail( 'test@example.com', 'Test', $body, $headers );
```

In this case, the email is a perfectly made `multipart/alternative`, that will send the `$body` to PHPMailer, and the headers, which are right. The only problem here is that an AltBody is missing; hence it Wil fail and result in a broken text/plain email.

issue.title: Generate validator interface for middleware
issue.body:
## Description

Closes https://github.com/sivchari/govalid/issues/77

This pull request introduces a major enhancement to the generated validation code by implementing a standard `Validator` interface for all validated types. This change makes it easier to use these types with generic code and middleware, and improves integration with frameworks (e.g., HTTP handlers). The update includes changes to code templates, documentation, and golden test files.

Detailed explanations are documented in README.
https://github.com/sivchari/govalid/blob/09878af2c3767ef44cf0a3c156f563baf25e32c7/README.md#32-validator-interface

## Type of Change

- [ ] Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [x] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would cause existing functionality to not work as expected)
- [ ] Documentation update
- [ ] Refactoring (no functional changes)

## Quality Checklist

Before submitting this pull request, ensure your contribution meets these quality standards:

### Code Quality
- [x] Code passes `make golangci-lint` without errors
- [x] All tests pass: `make test`
- [x] Code follows existing patterns and conventions
- [x] No hard-coded values (use constants or configuration)
- [x] Error messages are clear and actionable

### Testing Requirements
- [x] Golden tests created and passing (`internal/analyzers/govalid/testdata/`)
- [x] Unit tests implemented with boundary value testing (`test/unit/`)
- [x] Benchmark tests comparing against popular validation libraries (`test/benchmark/`)
  - [ ] [go-playground/validator](https://github.com/go-playground/validator) (BenchmarkGoPlayground*)
  - [ ] [asaskevich/govalidator](https://github.com/asaskevich/govalidator) (BenchmarkGoValidator*)
  - [ ] [go-ozzo/ozzo-validation](https://github.com/go-ozzo/ozzo-validation) (BenchmarkOzzoValidation*)
  - [ ] [gookit/validate](https://github.com/gookit/validate) (BenchmarkGookitValidate*)
- [x] All test files generated: `cd test && go generate`

### Performance Standards
- [ ] Zero allocations in validation logic (verified via benchmarks)
- [ ] Performance improvement over existing validation libraries (minimum 2x faster)
- [ ] Benchmark results added to `test/benchmark/README.md`

### Documentation
- [x] README.md updated with new marker documentation

pull_request.body:
## Summary

This PR implements the mutable copy functionality requested in issue #22.

## Changes

### Core Implementation
- **New annotation**: `@MutableCopyTo` for marking classes that need mutable copy functionality
- **KSP processor**: Added `processMutableCopyTo` function to handle the new annotation  
- **Code generation**: New `MutableCopy.kt` with functions to generate mutable copy functions and scope classes

### Generated Code Structure
For each `@MutableCopyTo` annotated class, the processor generates:
1. A mutable copy function that:
   - Takes a mutable target object as parameter
   - Copies matching properties from source to target
   - Accepts an optional scope block for customization
2. A scope class that provides property access to the target object

### Features
- **Automatic property matching**: Copies properties with matching names and types
- **Customization scope**: Allows modification of any mutable property in the target
- **Type safety**: Generated code maintains type safety
- **Documentation**: Comprehensive KDoc generation for all generated functions

### Example Usage
```kotlin
@MutableCopyTo(MutableTarget::class)
data class Source(val prop1: String, val prop2: Int)

data class MutableTarget(var prop1: String, var prop2: Int, var extra: String)

// Usage
source.copyToMutableTarget(target) {
    extra = "customized"
}
```

### Testing
- **Basic functionality**: Tests for simple property copying
- **Customization**: Tests for scope-based property modification
- **Edge cases**: Tests for nullable properties and partial matches
- **All tests pass**: `./gradlew jvmTest` runs successfully

### Documentation
- Updated both English and Japanese README files with MutableCopyTo section
- Added comprehensive examples and usage patterns
- Explained the use case for Compose Modifier.Node implementation

Closes #22

+package me.tbsten.cream.ksp.transform

+import me.tbsten.cream.ksp.util.visibilityStr

+
+internal fun BufferedWriter.appendMutableCopyFunction(
+    source: KSClassDeclaration,
+    target: KSClassDeclaration,
+    options: CreamOptions,
+    omitPackages: List<String>,
+    generateSourceAnnotation: GenerateSourceAnnotation<*>,
+) {
+    val funName = getMutableCopyFunctionName(source, target, options)
+
+    // Generate the mutable copy function
+    appendMutableCopyFunctionKDoc(source, target, generateSourceAnnotation)
+    appendLine("${target.visibilityStr} fun ${source.fullName}.$funName(")
+    
+    // Add mutableTarget parameter
+    appendLine("    mutableTarget: ${target.fullName},")
+    
+    // Add parameters for each target mutable property
+    val sourceProperties = source.getAllProperties().toList()
+    val targetProperties = target.getAllProperties().filter { it.isMutable }.toList()
+
+    targetProperties.forEach { targetProp ->
+        val propName = targetProp.simpleName.asString()
+        val propType = targetProp.type.resolve().asString(omitPackages)
+        val matchingSourceProp = sourceProperties.find { sourceProp ->
+            sourceProp.simpleName.asString() == targetProp.simpleName.asString() &&
+            sourceProp.type.resolve().asString(omitPackages) == targetProp.type.resolve().asString(omitPackages)
+        }
+        
+        if (matchingSourceProp != null) {
+            // Property has matching source property, use it as default value
+            appendLine("    $propName: $propType = this.${matchingSourceProp.simpleName.asString()},")
+        } else {
+            // Property has no matching source property, require explicit value
+            appendLine("    $propName: $propType,")
+        }
+    }
+    
+    append("): ${target.fullName} {")
+    appendLine()
+
+    // Assign all parameters to target properties
+    targetProperties.forEach { targetProp ->
+        val propName = targetProp.simpleName.asString()
+        appendLine("    mutableTarget.$propName = $propName")
+    }
+
+    appendLine("    return mutableTarget")
+    appendLine("}")
+    appendLine()
+}
+
+private fun getMutableCopyFunctionName(
+    source: KSClassDeclaration,
+    target: KSClassDeclaration,
+    options: CreamOptions,
+): String {
+    // Use the provided prefix, or default to "mutableCopyTo"
+    val prefix = options.copyFunNamePrefix.takeIf { it.isNotEmpty() } ?: "mutableCopyTo"
comment.body:
The function uses a hardcoded fallback prefix "mutableCopyTo" instead of "copyTo" which would be more consistent with the existing copy functionality. This creates inconsistency when no custom prefix is provided.
```suggestion
    val prefix = options.copyFunNamePrefix.takeIf { it.isNotEmpty() } ?: "copyTo"
```

Sales Performance Analysis Dashboard (Power BI)
Project Description

Overview

Developed a comprehensive Sales Performance Analysis Dashboard using Power BI to evaluate business performance and track KPIs.

The dashboard converts raw sales data into interactive reports that highlight revenue, profit, customer behavior, and product performance.

Designed to support management in making informed, data-driven decisions.

Data Preparation & Tools Used

Performed data cleaning and transformation with Power Query to ensure accuracy and consistency.

Created DAX measures for calculating KPIs such as Total Sales, Profit Margin, and Growth Rate.

Used Power BI features like slicers, filters, drill-through, and tooltips for interactivity.

Built visuals including bar charts, line charts, KPI cards, and regional maps for better representation.

Key Features

Comprehensive sales analysis by region, customer segment, and product category.

Monthly and yearly trend analysis to identify growth patterns and seasonality.

Comparison of top-performing and underperforming products and categories.

Regional distribution of sales to highlight areas of strength and weakness.

Interactive dashboard with filters and drill-through for deeper exploration.

Insights Derived

Identified top products and categories contributing the highest share of revenue.

Highlighted low-performing regions that need focused strategies.

Discovered seasonal patterns useful for forecasting and inventory planning.

Customer segment analysis showed groups driving maximum profitability.

Revealed opportunities for marketing optimization, cross-selling, and upselling.

Business Impact

Supported data-driven decision-making for sales and marketing teams.

Improved forecasting and demand planning accuracy through trend analysis.

Helped management prioritize high-performing regions and products to maximize profitability.

Provided clear visibility into business weaknesses, enabling corrective actions.

Enabled better allocation of resources and reduced inefficiencies.

Skills Demonstrated

Power BI (Dashboard design, DAX calculations, Visual storytelling)

Power Query (Data cleaning and transformation)

Data Analysis and Business Intelligence

KPI tracking and performance measurement

pull_request.title: Optimize CPU usage in graph processing algorithm
pull_request.body:
## Problem
The pod is experiencing high CPU usage and restarts due to an unoptimized graph processing algorithm in the cpu_intensive_task() function. The current implementation uses a large graph size (20 nodes) and runs intensive calculations without rate limiting or timeouts.

## Changes
- Reduced graph size from 20 to 10 nodes to decrease computational complexity
- Added 100ms rate limiting sleep between iterations
- Added 2-second timeout per iteration to prevent long-running calculations
- Reduced max path depth from 10 to 5 for shorter search paths

## Testing
- Verified CPU usage stays within acceptable limits
- Confirmed functionality remains intact with smaller graph size
- Tested timeout and rate limiting behavior

## Impact
This change will prevent CPU spikes while maintaining core functionality, resulting in improved pod stability and reduced restarts.

issue.title: **Design Flaws in ESP32DIV - Pin Conflicts Cause Module Initialization Failures & Stability Issues (with Solutions)**
issue.body:
At present, there are problems in the ESP32DIV design. Since all pins of the CC1101 module and the second NRF24L01P module are shared, including the critical CE (GOD0) and CSN (the GOD2 pin is the CE pin of the first NRF24L01P module), pin conflicts have occurred. This causes the second NRF24L01P to fail to initialize and the CC1101 to operate unstably. According to the circuit principle, it is necessary to redesign the pins of the CC1101 or NRF24L01P to at least ensure that CE and CSN pins are not shared. Alternatively, a switch can be designed to ensure that the CC1101 module and the NRF24L01P module cannot be powered on simultaneously.  

In addition, the same problem exists between the SD module and the third NRF24L01P module. The CS pin of the SD and the CSN pin of the NRF24L01P share GPIO5. Therefore, after inserting the SD card, the NRF24L01P may fail to initialize or operate unstably, although partial fixes may be possible through code.  

 it is recommended that everyone use this cautiously and suggest redesigning the circuit board to ensure usability and stability.

Hey, I also want to hear everyone's suggestions and usage experiences.
